      {
        "id": "mineru_PPT_ch7_page_136_2",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "If A in (11) is square, n × n, then (11) maps Rn into Rn. If this A is nonsingular, so that A-1 exists (see Sec. 7.8), then multiplication of (11) by A-1 from the left and use of A-1A = I gives the inverse transformation",
        "bbox": [
          0.05533333333333333,
          0.24977777777777777,
          0.938,
          0.4622222222222222
        ],
        "order": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_PPT_ch7_page_136_3",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "It maps every y = yo onto that x, which by (11) is mapped onto yo. The inverse of a linear transformation is itself linear, because it is given by a matrix, as (14) shows.",
        "bbox": [
          0.056666666666666664,
